Animadvertendum autem est, formam rei inesse (ut ex iis quae dicta sunt plane liquet) instantiis universis et singulis, inquibus res ipsa inest ⁹⁶3 aliter enim forma non esset: itaque nulla plane dari potest instantia contradictoria. Attamen longe magis conspicua invenitur forma et evidens in aliquibus instantiis, quam in aliis; in iis videlicet, ubi minus cohibita est natura formae et impedita et redacta in ordinem per naturas alias. Hujusmodi autem instantias, elucescentias vel instantias ostensivas appellare consuevimus ⁹⁷. Pergendum ita- que est ad vindemiationem ipsam primam deforma calidi.

Per universas et singulas instantias, natura cujus limi- tatio est calor videtur esse motus. Hoc autem maxime ostenditur in flamma, quae perpetuo movetur3 et in liquoribus ferventibus aut bullientibus qui etiam per- petuo moventur. The argument would have been periectly correct, not only with reference to ‘natures' but also with reference to ‘causes' if he had said that, wherever the supposed form is, there the thing itself must be. Thus, if we start the hypothesis that motion is causally connected with heat, and we find, as a matter of fact, that motion is always attended by an increase of temperature, the hypothesis becomes an ascer- taiued truth. We can, as 1 have so frequently stated, argue with certainty from the cause to the effect, but not from the effect to the cause.
